<refentry xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:db="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:scilab="http://www.scilab.org"  xml:lang="en" xml:id="cylinder">
    <refnamediv>
        <refname>cylinder</refname>
        <refpurpose>Computes cylinder coordinates</refpurpose>
    </refnamediv>
    <refsynopsisdiv>
        <title>Syntax</title>
        <synopsis>[x, y, z] = cylinder(r, n)</synopsis>
    </refsynopsisdiv>
    <refsection>
        <title>Arguments</title>
        <variablelist>
            <varlistentry>
                <term>r</term>
                <listitem>
                    <para>Radius. Default value is 1.</para>
                </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
            <varlistentry>
                <term>n</term>
                <listitem>
                    <para>Number of points around circumference. Default value is 20.</para>
                </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
            <varlistentry>
                <term>x, y, z</term>
                <listitem>
                    <para>Computed Cartesian coordinates.</para>
                </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
    </refsection>
    <refsection>
        <title>Description</title>
        <para>
            <literal>cylinder</literal> returns the Cartesian coordinates of a cylinder (with height equal to 1) without drawing it. The returned coordinates can be then plotted using <link linkend="surf">surf</link>.
        </para>
        <para>
            If <literal>r</literal> is a scalar, then each coordinate is a <literal>2 x (n+1)</literal> matrix. If <literal>r</literal> is a vector, then each coordinate is a <literal>size(r, "*") x (n+1)</literal> matrix.
        </para>
    </refsection>
    <refsection>
        <title>Examples</title>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">Cylinder with radius equal to 1:</emphasis></para>
        <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
scf();
[x, y, z] = cylinder();
surf(x, y, z);
gcf().color_map = jet(64);
 ]]></programlisting>
        <scilab:image>
            scf();
            [x, y, z] = cylinder();
            surf(x, y, z);
            gcf().color_map = jet(64);
        </scilab:image>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">Cylinder with radius equal to 3, more points over circumference, and height equal to 20:</emphasis></para>
        <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
scf();
[x, y, z] = cylinder(3, 40);
surf(x, y, 20 * z);
gcf().color_map = jet(64);
 ]]></programlisting>
        <scilab:image>
            scf();
            [x, y, z] = cylinder(3, 40);
            surf(x, y, 20 * z);
            gcf().color_map = jet(64);
        </scilab:image>
    </refsection>
    <refsection>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">Cylinder with decreasing radius (Cone):</emphasis></para>
        <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
scf();
[x, y, z] = cylinder(10:-0.2:0, 40);
surf(x, y, z, "LineStyle", "none");
gcf().color_map = jet(64);
 ]]></programlisting>
        <scilab:image>
            scf();
            [x, y, z] = cylinder(10:-0.2:0, 40);
            surf(x, y, z, "LineStyle", "none");
            gcf().color_map = jet(64);
        </scilab:image>
    </refsection>
